ce:section.ce:para:
Previous works have shown that the use of citric acid and urea as carbon sources may afford long wavelength emission upon different synthetic conditions [21]. In this work, a dual emissive Cl, N-doped CDs (Cl, N-CDs) was synthesized by the one-pot solvothermal method using urea and citric acid as nitrogen and carbon sources, and cyanuric chloride as doping substance (Scheme 1
                     ). Notably, the Cl, N-CDs display two broad emission bands in the range of 400 – 570 nm and 580 – 720 nm with a single excitation of 410 nm. The optimal emission wavelength reaches 650 nm and the stokes shift is as large as 240 nm, which is superior to most of the Cl-doped emissive CDs (Table 1
                     ). Interestingly, the range of emission bands of this Cl, N-CDs is also beneficial to plant lighting as the synergistic effects of blue and red emission light are significant for plant photosynthesis. In addition, the quantum yield (QY) of Cl, N-CDs was measured to be 22.06 %, which is higher than most of the reported Cl-doped CDs (Table 1). The fluorescence of Cl, N-CDs was specifically quenched by AmB among twenty-seven kinds of common veterinary drugs, twenty kinds of natural amino acids, and twenty-one kinds of other common substances including carbohydrates, vitamins, and ions, showing its high selectivity toward AmB. The detection limit (LOD) of AmB was 6.67 nM, which is comparable with the chromatography method (Table S1). Furthermore, the determination of AmB by the proposed fluorescent method was practically applied in milk and wastewater. As far as we know, this is the first example of fluorescent detection and quantification of AmB.
